## What Is a Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamond?

A lab grown cushion cut diamond is a diamond — identical in chemical composition, crystal structure, and optical properties to a mined diamond — produced in a controlled laboratory environment using either High Pressure High Temperature (HPHT) or Chemical Vapour Deposition (CVD) processes, then cut into the cushion shape. The only difference between a lab grown cushion and a natural cushion is origin. Under magnification, in spectroscopic testing, in brilliance, in hardness, and in every measure that affects appearance — they are the same stone.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. The [lab grown cushion cut diamond](/cushion-cut-diamond) has become the dominant choice for buyers seeking 2ct and above in the cushion shape. The reason is simple arithmetic: at 3ct, a GIA D-VVS1 lab cushion costs $5,962 from Blue Nile. The equivalent natural stone starts at $32,692. No independent gemologist, looking at both stones without a certificate, can tell which is which. The decision to pay $26,730 more for natural origin requires a clear values-based reasoning that every buyer deserves to examine before committing.

What most buyers do not know before entering the lab cushion market: there are two visually distinct cushion sub-types, and the certification document does not explain the visual difference clearly. Understanding this — what I call The Modified Brilliant Split — is the single most important piece of knowledge for any lab cushion buyer.

Full credentials and methodology at **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**.

