## The Modified Brilliant Split

The Modified Brilliant Split is the most important concept for any lab grown cushion buyer — and the one that most buyers discover only after purchase, when they realise the stone they received looks different from what they expected.

![The Modified Brilliant Split infographic showing cushion modified brilliant crushed ice facet pattern versus cushion brilliant chunky facet pattern side by side with certification comparison](/images/lab-grown-cushion-modified-brilliant-split.avif)

Blue Nile's lab grown cushion inventory contains two distinct cut sub-types, described differently in GIA and IGI certificates:

**Cushion Modified Brilliant (the "crushed ice" stone).** The cushion modified brilliant has additional facets on the pavilion that create a fine, uniform sparkle pattern — what the industry calls "crushed ice." When you look at a cushion modified brilliant face-up, you see a dense, glittering carpet of small light reflections without distinct individual facet flashes. It is bright, consistent, and scintillates uniformly under all lighting. This is the sub-type that dominates lab grown cushion production and accounts for the majority of BN's lab cushion inventory.

**Cushion Brilliant (the "chunky facet" stone).** The cushion brilliant has fewer, larger pavilion facets — closer in structure to a round brilliant's pavilion. When you look at a cushion brilliant face-up, you see distinct, larger flashes of light with visible facet patterns. It shows more fire (colour dispersion) than the modified brilliant, resembles an old mine cut more closely in character, and creates a warmer, more traditional diamond look. The cushion brilliant is the minority sub-type in BN's lab cushion range but is represented.

**Why the GIA cert does not warn you clearly.** The GIA grading report for a lab grown cushion states "Cushion Modified" or "Cushion" in the cut description field — a one-word or two-word designation that most buyers do not notice, do not understand, and do not think to ask about. There is no photograph on a GIA cert. There is no facet diagram for cushion shapes. A buyer who selects a lab grown cushion on BN, filters by colour and clarity, and purchases without checking the specific cut sub-type description may receive either a crushed ice stone or a chunky facet stone — they are two different looking diamonds at the same listed quality grades.

**How to avoid The Modified Brilliant Split trap.** When viewing any lab grown cushion on BN, check the product description line that reads "Cushion Modified" or "Cushion." Request the HD video (BN provides 360° video for most stones) and view it under both the standard bright light (which favours crushed ice) and note the size of individual flashes. If the video shows a uniform glitter pattern, it is a modified brilliant. If it shows distinct, larger, moving flashes, it is a cushion brilliant.

**Which sub-type should you buy?** For engagement ring settings where the stone is viewed primarily from above — halos, pavé bands, most standard settings — the crushed ice modified brilliant is the right choice: it creates more uniform visual impact and photographs better. For buyers who prefer a warmer, more characterful stone with visible facet patterns — those attracted to the old mine cut aesthetic but not the estate premium — the cushion brilliant sub-type is worth seeking specifically.

