## The Certification Gap

The Certification Gap is the price difference between an IGI-certified lab grown cushion and a GIA-certified lab grown cushion of identical stated quality — and it is larger, and less justified, than most buyers realise before entering the lab diamond market.

![The Certification Gap chart showing IGI vs GIA pricing on lab grown cushion modified brilliants at 1.5ct, 2ct, and 3ct with the premium annotated and value recommendation](/images/lab-grown-cushion-certification-gap.avif)

**The numbers at 2ct.** A 2ct IGI D-IF Ideal Cut Cushion Modified lab at Blue Nile: [$4,782](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27593401?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). A 2ct GIA D-IF Ideal Cut Cushion Modified lab at Blue Nile: [$6,792](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26964675?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Same carat weight, same colour grade (D), same clarity grade (IF), same cut grade (Ideal), same shape (Cushion Modified). Different certification house. Price difference: **$2,010 — a 42% premium for GIA over IGI** on the same stated quality.

**Why The Certification Gap exists for lab diamonds.** GIA is the most prestigious certification body in the diamond industry, established in 1931, and its grades carry higher market recognition than IGI (founded 1975). In the natural diamond market, GIA certification commands a meaningful resale premium because natural diamond grading consistency matters for a stone that may be bought and sold multiple times over decades. In the lab diamond market — where resale value is substantially lower than natural and stones are not expected to be resold as appreciating assets — the GIA premium represents brand recognition rather than practical buying advantage.

**When to choose GIA for a lab cushion.** If you intend to insure the stone at a high declared value and your insurer requires GIA documentation, choose GIA. If you are buying the stone as a gift that will be appraised and the recipient's jeweller only recognises GIA grades, choose GIA. If you care about the resale market for lab diamonds — where GIA certification does carry a small secondary market premium — choose GIA.

**When to choose IGI for a lab cushion.** If your priority is stone quality per dollar — and it should be for most buyers in the lab market — IGI offers the same grade descriptions at substantially lower prices. A 2ct IGI D-VVS1 Ideal Cushion Modified at [$2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) represents extraordinary value. The $4,176 you save versus a comparable GIA D-IF could purchase an exceptional pavé setting. IGI grading of lab diamonds is independently verified and their lab-grown diamond grading is considered reliable by the industry.

