## Elongated Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamond

The elongated lab grown cushion cut — length-to-width ratio of 1.15:1 to 1.30:1 — is a distinct sub-category within the lab cushion market that has grown rapidly as buyers seek the finger-lengthening effect of oval-like shapes at cushion prices. For a full breakdown of this sub-type, see the [elongated cushion cut diamond guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond).

Key differences from standard lab cushion: elongated lab cushions are available at the same price points as square lab cushions but have a measurably larger finger coverage at equivalent carat weights. A 2ct elongated cushion modified brilliant at approximately 9.2mm × 7.2mm covers significantly more of the finger than a 2ct square cushion at approximately 8mm × 8mm — the elongated form reads "larger" even at identical carat weights.

The Modified Brilliant Split applies equally to elongated lab cushions. The elongated cushion modified brilliant shows crushed ice across its entire elongated face-up surface; the elongated cushion brilliant shows distinct, larger flashes along the long axis that create a different visual rhythm. For buyers seeking the "big and bright" look: elongated modified brilliant. For buyers seeking the "character and fire" look: elongated cushion brilliant.

---

## Lab Grown Cushion Cut Engagement Ring Settings

Choosing the right setting for a lab grown cushion cut diamond follows the same principles as for natural cushions — with the added freedom that the budget savings from choosing lab allow you to invest significantly more in setting quality. For comprehensive setting analysis, see the [cushion cut engagement ring guide](/cushion-cut-diamond-engagement-ring).

**Halo settings with lab cushion.** The [lab grown cushion halo ring](/halo-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) is the most requested configuration because the halo amplifies the face-up size of the center stone — already larger at lab budget levels — and creates the maximum total diamond look. A 2ct D-VVS1 lab cushion in a pavé halo setting costs less in total than a 1ct natural cushion in the same setting. The halo's melee diamonds can be either natural or lab to match or contrast with the center stone.

**Solitaire settings with lab cushion.** A lab grown cushion in a simple four-prong solitaire is the strongest value proposition for buyers who want the stone to dominate without a supporting setting structure. The 3ct GIA D-VVS1 at $5,962 in a plain yellow gold four-prong solitaire — a classic setting available from most jewellers for $400–$800 — creates a ring that reads as an exceptional piece at a fraction of what a comparable natural would require.

**Pavé settings with lab cushion.** The pavé band pairs well with the cushion modified brilliant's crushed ice pattern — both create a fine, uniform sparkle surface that reads as a single continuous light source on the hand. The combination of a modified brilliant cushion center with a pavé shank is the most photographically impactful configuration for lab cushion buyers.

**Three-stone settings.** For [three-stone cushion rings](/three-stone-cushion-cut-diamond-ring), lab grown side stones allow buyers to use significant carat weight in the flanking positions without the steep natural premium for side stone matching. Two 0.5ct lab cushion side stones cost a fraction of natural equivalents and are indistinguishable from natural in a completed three-stone ring.

---

## Metal Choice for Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamonds

Lab grown cushion cut diamonds in D-E colour look their best in white metal — platinum or 14K white gold. The colourless appearance of D-E stones reads most cleanly against white metal with no warm reflections contaminating the stone's colourless appearance.

For buyers who prefer yellow or rose gold: choose F-G colour lab cushion rather than D-E. In yellow gold settings, the metal's warm reflection against the stone's pavilion creates a slight warmth in the stone's appearance regardless of colour grade. Paying the D colour premium for a stone set in yellow gold is spending money on a visual improvement the setting will partially negate.

Lab grown cushion cut diamonds respond particularly well to rose gold settings. The cool white brilliance of a modified brilliant cushion against rose gold creates a strong contrast that makes both the stone and the metal appear more vivid.

---

> "The Modified Brilliant Split is the piece of knowledge that transforms a lab cushion purchase from a price decision into a quality decision. Two buyers at the same BN price point, selecting by colour and clarity only, can receive stones that look visually distinct from each other. The crushed ice pattern and the chunky facet pattern are both valid choices — but they are different aesthetic choices that serve different preferences.
>
> The buyer who specifically wants the crushed ice look — maximum uniform brilliance, looks remarkable in photos — should filter for 'Cushion Modified' in the cut description. The buyer who wants the warmer, more characterful look closer to an old mine cut should look for 'Cushion' (non-modified). Most buyers want crushed ice and do not know they need to look for the word 'Modified' to get it." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

> "The Certification Gap surprises buyers who enter the lab market expecting GIA to always cost more and always be worth it. At 3ct, GIA D-VVS1 Ideal is $5,962 and IGI D-VVS1 Ideal is $6,215 — GIA is cheaper. At 2ct, GIA D-IF is $6,792 and IGI D-IF is $4,782 — IGI is $2,010 cheaper. The lab diamond market does not follow the consistent GIA premium pattern of the natural market because supply and inventory levels differ dramatically between certification houses at each quality tier.
>
> The practical advice: never assume the price hierarchy. Check actual listed prices for the specific grade combination you want before deciding whether GIA premium is justified in your specific purchase scenario." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

> "For buyers uncertain whether lab grown is right for them: the correct test is not to look at lab cushions online. It is to visit a jeweller who carries both lab and natural cushions, look at a matched pair in person under the same lighting, and see if you can tell the difference. Almost no buyer can. The question that follows — whether the difference matters anyway — is the only question that determines whether natural is worth 5–10 times the price." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

