## Frequently Asked Questions About Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamonds

### What is a lab grown cushion cut diamond?

A lab grown cushion cut diamond is a diamond produced in a laboratory environment — chemically, optically, and physically identical to a mined diamond — cut into the cushion shape. It has the same hardness (10 Mohs), the same refractive index, the same brilliance, and the same grading criteria as a natural cushion. The only difference is origin: a laboratory rather than a mine.

### How much cheaper is a lab grown cushion vs natural?

At 1.5ct, lab cushions are approximately 75–80% cheaper than natural equivalents. At 2ct, the savings are approximately 81%. At 3ct, 82%. At 4ct, approximately 91%. The savings compound with carat weight because natural diamond prices increase exponentially per carat as rarity increases; lab grown diamond prices increase much more gradually as production scales.

### What is the Modified Brilliant Split?

The Modified Brilliant Split is the distinction between two cushion cut sub-types: the cushion modified brilliant (crushed ice pattern — fine, uniform sparkle) and the cushion brilliant (chunky facet pattern — larger, distinct flashes). GIA and IGI certificates describe the cut type as "Cushion Modified" or "Cushion" in the cut section. The visual difference is significant and the two sub-types suit different aesthetic preferences.

### Which is better — IGI or GIA for a lab grown cushion?

It depends on budget and purpose. GIA is more prestigious and carries a higher resale recognition premium. IGI is significantly cheaper for the same stated quality grade. At 2ct D-IF, the GIA premium is $2,010 (42%) over IGI. If you prioritise stone quality per dollar and are not concerned with secondary market recognition, IGI is the correct choice. If you require the highest certification recognition for insurance or resale purposes, choose GIA.

### Can you tell the difference between lab and natural cushion diamonds?

No independent gemologist can visually distinguish a lab grown cushion from a natural cushion of equivalent quality without advanced spectroscopic equipment that detects trace element differences in crystal growth. Neither can retail jewellers, photographers, or guests at the event where the ring is worn. The difference exists at the molecular level and in the certificate's origin notation.

### What is the best lab grown cushion cut diamond for an engagement ring?

For most buyers, the [IGI 2ct D-VVS1 Ideal Cushion Modified at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the strongest recommendation: D colour (top), VVS1 (genuinely clean), Ideal cut, 2ct face-up presence, and the crushed ice modified brilliant pattern optimised for engagement ring viewing. Budget remaining after the stone funds an exceptional setting.

### What colour grade should I choose for a lab grown cushion?

D-E colour for white metal settings (platinum, white gold). F-G colour for yellow or rose gold settings — in warm metal, the D-E colour premium is partially cancelled by metal reflection, making F-G a better value choice. Avoid going below G in any setting; H and below may show visible warmth in the body of a cushion cut at 2ct and above.

### What cut grade should I choose?

Ideal or Excellent cut for maximum light return. Good cut grades may save money but sacrifice measurable brilliance that is visible to the naked eye in a cushion modified brilliant. The cut grade is the most impactful quality factor for visual appearance in a lab cushion — do not compromise on it.

### Is a 2ct or 3ct lab cushion worth buying over a 1ct natural?

For most buyers, yes. A 1ct natural GIA G-VS1 cushion modified from Blue Nile is approximately $1,891. A 2ct IGI D-VVS1 Ideal lab cushion modified is $2,606. The additional $715 buys double the carat weight, a better colour grade (D vs G), better clarity (VVS1 vs VS1), and a larger face-up appearance. The visual and quality case for the 2ct lab over the 1ct natural is strong at this budget level.

### What is the difference between cushion modified brilliant and cushion brilliant?

The cushion modified brilliant has additional pavilion facets creating a "crushed ice" sparkle pattern — dense, uniform, and photographically brilliant. The cushion brilliant has fewer, larger pavilion facets creating distinct flash patterns more similar to a round brilliant or old mine cut. Both are graded equally by GIA and IGI for cut quality; the choice is purely aesthetic. For engagement rings viewed face-up in photos: modified brilliant. For buyers who prefer characterful, warmer-looking stones: cushion brilliant.

### Can I get a lab grown cushion certified after purchase?

Yes. GIA and IGI both accept lab grown diamonds for grading through their standard submission processes. However, purchasing an already-certified stone from BN is strongly recommended — you know the exact quality before buying, and the certification is included in the price.

### Does a lab grown cushion hold its value?

Lab grown diamonds currently depreciate faster than natural diamonds on the secondary market, as ongoing production keeps supply high and prices declining year over year. A lab cushion purchased today may be worth significantly less in resale in five years. For buyers purchasing an engagement ring as a long-term sentimental object rather than a financial asset, this is not a relevant concern. For buyers treating the purchase as an investment, natural diamonds retain value better.

### How do I know if my lab cushion is a Modified Brilliant?

Check the product description on Blue Nile — it will state "Cushion Modified" or "Cushion" in the cut description. On GIA and IGI certificates, the shape and cut description field will read "Cushion Modified Brilliant" or "Cushion Brilliant." If purchasing from a retailer whose listing does not clearly identify the sub-type, request the certificate before purchasing.

---

## Final Verdict: Which Lab Grown Cushion Cut Is Right for You?

**Buy the 2ct IGI D-VVS1 Ideal Cushion Modified at $2,606 if:** You want the strongest value play in the lab cushion market — maximum quality grade combination at a price that is impossible in the natural market. The [IGI D-VVS1 at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the benchmark purchase in this post — stop reading when you find this stone, verify the HD video shows a crushed ice pattern, and buy it.

**Buy the 3ct GIA D-VVS1 Ideal Cushion Modified at $5,962 if:** You want a genuinely large center stone with prestige GIA certification and the highest colour grade. The [3ct GIA D-VVS1 at $5,962](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the post's most compelling premium pick — GIA certified, D colour, 3ct face-up impact, $5,962 total. This would cost $32,692+ in the natural market.

**Buy a 1.5ct IGI E-VVS2 Excellent at $1,422 if:** You have a strict budget and want lab quality without compromising to lower colour or clarity grades. The [1.5ct IGI E-VVS2 at $1,422](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28961887?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry point that still delivers near-top colour and clean clarity at a price that leaves room for an excellent setting.

**Buy a Cushion Brilliant (non-modified) if:** You specifically want the chunky facet, warmer-character look rather than the crushed ice pattern. Filter for "Cushion Lab" (non-modified) in BN's search and verify via HD video that you see distinct, larger flashes rather than uniform glitter. This sub-type suits buyers who prefer the character of an [old mine cut](/old-mine-cushion-cut-diamond) at modern lab pricing.

