## Expert Summary

The lab grown cushion cut diamond has done something no other product category in the jewellery market has managed: it has made 3ct and 4ct diamonds accessible to buyers who would previously have needed to spend $30,000–$85,000 to reach those sizes in a natural stone. A [3ct GIA D-VVS1 lab cushion at $5,962](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26315453?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is not a compromise product. It is a top-grade, GIA-certified diamond that is chemically identical to a $32,000 natural equivalent, and which no human eye can distinguish from its natural counterpart on the hand.

The two concepts every buyer must understand before purchasing: The Modified Brilliant Split (check whether your stone is "Cushion Modified" or "Cushion" — they look different) and The Certification Gap (IGI and GIA are priced inconsistently across size tiers in the lab market — always compare actual prices, not certification assumptions).

The recommended purchase for most buyers remains the [2ct IGI D-VVS1 Ideal Cushion Modified at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Everything above that budget is a preference upgrade — more carat weight, GIA certification, higher clarity. Everything below that budget is a size or quality trade. The 2ct D-VVS1 is the point where price, quality, and face-up impact converge into the most rational single purchase in the lab cushion range.

